    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-07-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-07-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="108"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d108">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/1403.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador to France</gloss>
                        to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Summary.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-07-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 31, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have just received a note verbale from the Minister for Foreign Affairs dated
                    July 29, of which the following is a translation: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Summary of translation: The Minister acknowledges the Ambassador’s note
                            verbale of July 24 in regard to recognition of the Chinese Government.
                            The French Government considers that under existing circumstances the
                            conditions for recognition seem far from fulfilled. Until the
                            Provisional Government shall have been succeeded by a regularly
                            constituted parliamentary régime, according to the properly expressed
                            desire of the people, and until such new and well-established government
                            shall have given formal guaranty of treaty stipulations and rights of
                            foreigners in China, the French Government does not consider that the
                            question of recognition of the Chinese Government can be advantageously
                            advanced.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
